*Modified for stylasterid corals from [Purifying RNA from Plant Tissues] (https://documents.thermofisher.com/TFS-Assets/LSG/manuals/purelink_rna_mini_kit_man.pdf#page=32.07)*

## OBJECTIVE

Extract and purify high-quality RNA for transcriptome assembly. 

## SAMPLES

Preparation

1. Pre-temp centrifuge to 4˚C. Pre-heat DEPC-treated water to 65˚C (50 uL per sample).
2. Wipe down no-DNA laminar flow hood with 10% bleach, RNase Away, and 70% ethanol. 
3. Wipe mortar and pestle, hammer, chisel, tweezers, spatula, and weigh boat down with 10% bleach, 70% etOH, and RNase away.
4. Place items from step 3, a falcon tube for working lysis buffer, epi-tubes (# of samples), a tube rack, and DEPC treated H2O in the hood and UV sterilize for 20-30 minutes.
5. Wipe down low DNA bench. 
6. Prepare working Trizol buffer by adding 10 uL 2-mercaptoethanol per 1 mL Trizol to an RNase free 15 mL falcon tube.

> - 2-mercaptoethanol volume to add to buffer = (# samples + 2 for error) x (2 lysis rounds) x (1500 uL) x 0.01
> - Trizol volume = (# samples + 2 for error) x (2 lysis rounds) x (1500 uL) - 2-mercaptoethanol volume


7. Prepare 6M HCl (if necessary) by adding 500 uL DEPC Treated H2O and VWR BDH ACS grade hydrochloric acid 36.5-38% in hood. 
8. Obtain LN2 and ice.

Homogenizing Coral

*See https://cdn.coastalscience.noaa.gov/cdhc/docs/Tissue_Homogenization.pdf*

9. Add LN2 to styrofoam box with cryo-safe dividers. Place spatulas, tweezers, chisel, and epi-tubes for samples in LN2 to chill. 
10. Pre‐chill clean mortar and pestle by filling with LN2 and letting it evaporate twice before adding tissue sample. 
11. Place large coral fragment in a weigh boat, use hammer and chisel to obtain ~ 2cm fragment of coral branch tip.
12. Add fragments to mortar and fill halfway with LN2. Let the LN2 evaporate before grinding with the pre‐chilled pestle.
13. Place hand over mortar and carefully hammer fragments into smaller chunks with pestle. Once in small chunks, thoroughly grind coral until it's a fine powder. 

> Intermittently add LN2 to your sample to prevent thawing and to allow ease of grinding tissue.

14. Obtain epi-tube from LN2, then use pre‐chilled spatulas to dispense ground tissue from mortar into tube.
Do not close tubes until all nitrogen vapors have evaporated to avoid pressure build up from the nitrogen gas.
15. Place samples on dry ice (or LN2) until next steps.

Lysis

16. In fume hood, add 5 uL 6M HCl to powder to each sample to neutralize CaCO3. 
17. Add 1500 uL working lysis buffer (Trizol prepared with 2–mercaptoethanol) to each sample tube.
18. Vortex the lysate to disperse the sample. 
19. Incubate in Trizol for 5 minutes at room temperature. Clean low DNA bench in the meantime.
20. Centrifuge at 1,000 × g, 4°C for 2 minutes. 
21. Transfer TRIzol supernatant to a fresh 2 mL RNase-free tube. Discard skeleton pellet. You should have ~1400 uL trizol
22. Add 280 uL (0.2 mL per 1 mL Trizol) chloroform, shake vigorously by hand for 15 seconds until solution is milky. Do not vortex.
23. Centrifuge at 12,000 x g for 30 minutes at 4°C. Place supernatant in new tube for extraction. Keep samples on ice.

> Note: After centrifugation, the mixture separates into a lower, red phenol-chloroform phase, an interphase, and a colorless upper aqueous phase which contains the RNA. The volume of the aqueous upper phase is ~600 μL.

Binding

24. On ice, transfer ~400 μL of the colorless, upper phase containing the RNA to a fresh RNase–free tube.
25. Add an equal volume 70% ethanol (400 uL) to obtain a final ethanol concentration of 35%. Vortex to mix well.
26. Invert the tube to disperse any visible precipitate that may form after adding ethanol.
27. Transfer up to 650 μL of your sample to the Spin Cartridge with a Collection Tube. 
28. Centrifuge at 12,000 × g for 15 seconds at 4˚C. Discard the flow-through, dab rim of collection tube by tapping against kim wipe face down, and reinsert the Spin Cartridge in the same Collection Tube.
29. Repeat Steps 28-29 until the entire sample (all lysate) is processed.

Washing

30. Add 700 μL Wash Buffer I to the Spin Cartridge. Centrifuge at 12,000 × g for 15 seconds at 4˚C. Discard the flow-through and the Collection Tube and place the Spin Cartridge into a new Collection Tube.
31. Add 500 μL Wash Buffer II to the Spin Cartridge.

> Make sure wash buffer II has ethanol added!
> When adding buffer, rinse sides of spin column with buffer.

32. Let buffer sit on column for 1 minute.
33. Centrifuge at 12,000 × g for 15 seconds at 4˚C. Discard the flow-through and reinsert the Spin Cartridge in the same Collection Tube.
34. Repeat Wash Buffer II steps twice more for a total of three washes.
25. Centrifuge the Spin Cartridge once more with collection tube at 12,000 × g for 1 minute at 4˚C to dry the membrane with attached RNA. Discard the Collection Tube and insert the Spin Cartridge into a Recovery Tube.

Elution

26. Add 25 μL 65˚C RNase-Free Water to the center of the Spin Cartridge
27. Incubate at room temperature for 1 minute.
28. Centrifuge the Spin Cartridge for 2 minutes at 12,000 × g at 4˚C.
29. Add another 25 uL 65˚C RNase free water to spin cartridge. Incubate for 1 minute.
30. Centrifuge the Spin Cartridge for 2 minutes at 12,000 × g at 4˚C.
29. Aliquot 10 uL of each sample in a PCR strip tube for downstream quality checks to avoid freeze-thaw cycles. 





